6. Authentication System
Token Flow

User submits email and password to POST /api/auth/login
Backend fetches user with .select('+password'), compares with bcrypt
On match, signs a JWT: jwt.sign({ id, role }, JWT_SECRET, { expiresIn: '7d' })
Returns { user, token } — password field is stripped by toJSON()
Frontend stores token in localStorage under key ps_token
Axios request interceptor attaches Authorization: Bearer <token> to every request
Backend authenticate middleware verifies the token and attaches req.user
On 401 response (expired or invalid token), the axios response interceptor clears localStorage and redirects to /mentorship/login

Registration Flow
Mentee registration — name, email, password, university. No code required. Role defaults to mentee.
Mentor registration — same fields plus mentorCode. Backend finds the MentorCode document, verifies isUsed === false, creates the user with role: 'mentor', sets code.isUsed = true and code.usedBy = newUser._id.
Admin registration — requires a valid AdminInvite token in the URL (/admin/register?token=xxx). The page validates the token before showing the form. On submit, the backend validates again (double-check), creates the user with role: 'admin', and marks the invite as used. Tokens expire and can be revoked. Each token is single-use.
Password Security
Passwords are hashed with bcryptjs at cost factor 12 (approximately 300ms per hash — fast enough for UX, slow enough to resist brute force). The password field has select: false in Mongoose, meaning it is never returned in query results unless explicitly requested with .select('+password'). The toJSON() method on the User model also explicitly deletes the password field before serialisation as a second layer of protection.

