9. Frontend Architecture
Routing
All routing uses React Router v6 with the declarative <Routes> and <Route> API. There is no conditional rendering to switch between sections — every section has its own URL subtree:
/                           Landing page
/beauty                     Beauty shop home
/beauty/product/:id         Single product detail
/mentorship                 Public mentorship splash
/mentorship/login           Login
/mentorship/register        Register (mentor or mentee)
/mentorship/mentor/home     Mentor dashboard (protected: mentor, admin)
/mentorship/mentor/mentees  Mentor's mentee list (protected: mentor, admin)
/mentorship/mentee/home     Mentee dashboard (protected: mentee, admin)
/requirements               Requirements shop home
/requirements/checkout      Order form (protected: any authenticated)
/news                       News board
/admin                      Admin dashboard (protected: admin)
/admin/register             Admin registration via invite token
Protected Routes
ProtectedRoute reads from AuthContext. If no user is present, it redirects to /mentorship/login with the intended destination in location.state.from. After login, the Login page reads this state and redirects back. If a user is present but their role is not in allowedRoles, they are redirected to their correct home page rather than a generic error.
State Management
There is no Redux or Zustand. State is managed with three tools:
React Context — AuthContext manages the authenticated user, token, login, register, and logout. CartContext manages the shopping cart. Both are provided at the root of the app.
Local component state — useState and useEffect for page-level data fetching, form state, and UI toggles.
sessionStorage — The cart is backed up to sessionStorage on every change and rehydrated on load, so a page refresh does not empty the cart. Idempotency keys for orders are also stored in sessionStorage so crash-then-retry scenarios work correctly.
localStorage — The JWT token and the mentee first-year checklist are stored in localStorage for persistence across sessions.
Service Layer
Every data-fetching operation goes through a service file in src/services/. Each service file exposes a plain object of async functions that call the axios instance and unwrap the response. They return typed data directly, not axios response objects. Components never import axios directly.
The axios instance in api.ts attaches the auth token to every request via a request interceptor and handles 401 responses globally via a response interceptor.

10. Image Upload System
Flow

Admin selects file(s) in the browser
Frontend shows a spec hint for the correct dimensions
Form submits as multipart/form-data via axios to the backend
Multer saves the raw file to uploads/temp/ with a random filename
The processImages middleware runs after Multer:

Reads the temp file with Sharp
Resizes and crops to the spec for the route's section
Converts to WebP at quality 82
Saves the final file to the section's upload directory
Deletes the temp file
Updates req.file/req.files with the new path


Controller reads the processed file path and stores it in the database
Express serves uploads/ as a static directory at /uploads

Dimension Specifications
SectionDimensionsAspect RatioCrop ModeBeauty800 × 800 px1:1 SquareCover (centred)Requirements900 × 600 px3:2 LandscapeCover (centred)News1200 × 630 px1.91:1 BannerCover (centred)
File Cleanup
When a product or post is deleted, the controller finds the stored image path, builds the absolute filesystem path, checks the file exists with fs.existsSync, and deletes it with fs.unlinkSync. The same happens when an image is replaced during an update — the old file is deleted before the new one is written.
Display Conventions
Every image in the UI is wrapped in a fixed aspect-ratio container with overflow-hidden. The <img> inside always has object-cover and w-full h-full. This means even if somehow a wrong-ratio image reaches the frontend, it will be cropped cleanly to fill its container rather than stretching.

11. Order System and Crash Safety
Normal Order Flow

User adds items to cart (client-side state + sessionStorage)
User navigates to checkout (requires authentication — redirected to login if not)
User fills delivery address and submits
Frontend generates an idempotency key: crypto.randomUUID() stored in sessionStorage keyed to a fingerprint of the cart contents
POST /api/requirements/order is called with items, address, notes, section, and idempotencyKey
Backend re-fetches item prices from MongoDB (client-submitted prices are ignored)
Stock availability is verified
Order document is created with the idempotency key
Cart is cleared, sessionStorage key is removed, user is navigated to requirements home

Crash Safety
If the network fails, times out, or the browser crashes after the request was sent but before the response arrived:

The cart is still in sessionStorage — it was not cleared
The idempotency key is still in sessionStorage
The order may or may not have been created depending on when the crash happened

The user sees a message telling them the connection was lost and that their order may still be processing. A "Retry" button is always visible. When they retry, the exact same idempotency key is sent. The server checks if an order with that key already exists for that user. If it does, it returns the existing order with HTTP 200 instead of creating a duplicate. If it does not, it creates a fresh order as normal.
The idempotencyKey field on the Order model has a unique sparse index. Sparse means existing orders without a key do not conflict with each other. Unique means no two orders can share the same key. In the rare race condition where two requests with the same key arrive simultaneously, the duplicate key MongoDB error is caught and handled — the controller fetches the existing order and returns it.
Order Status Lifecycle
pending → confirmed → shipped → delivered
                              ↘ cancelled (from any state)
Status is updated by admin only via PATCH /api/admin/orders/:id/status. The admin Orders tab shows all orders with expandable rows. Each expanded row shows the full item list, delivery address, customer notes, and a row of status buttons that highlight the current state and allow one-click transitions.

12. Mentorship Program
Registration
Mentees register freely at /mentorship/register with name, email, university, and password. Mentors use the same form but select the Mentor role, which reveals a code field. The code field validates in real time by calling POST /api/auth/validate-mentor-code with a 600ms debounce. The submit button stays disabled until the code shows as valid.
Assignment
Admin assigns mentees to mentors through the Assignment tab in the admin dashboard. The tab shows two panels side by side — unassigned mentees on the left and all mentors on the right. The mentor panel shows a colour-coded mentee count badge: green for zero, blue for one to three, amber for four to six, red for seven or more.
Clicking a mentee selects it (highlighted blue). Clicking a mentor selects it (highlighted gold). A confirmation banner appears showing both names with a Confirm button. On confirmation, PATCH /api/admin/assign-mentee sets mentee.mentorId = mentor._id. The mentee disappears from the unassigned list and the mentor's count increments, all without a page reload.
The Manage tab shows all current assignments. Each row has an Unassign button that calls the same endpoint with mentorId: null.
Dashboards
Mentor dashboard has two views toggled by a tab — Home (stats and tips) and My Mentees (list of assigned mentees with name, email, university, and WhatsApp link). Mentors only ever see their own mentees. The backend enforces this: User.find({ mentorId: req.user._id, role: 'mentee' }).
Mentee dashboard shows the assigned mentor's details, recent orders, a persistent first-year checklist (stored in localStorage per user), and quick links to all platform sections.

